observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

assign a focal person to do the reconciliation or set the manner and frequency of reconciliation to be able to prioritize tracing, locating and retrieving relevant documents to serve as a basis for adjustment in the entries;

reconcile the variance of ₱211,097.12 between the Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds consolidated balance at year end. These reciprocal accounts should have a zero consolidated balance at year end;

reconcile the variance between the General Ledger and Subsidiary Ledger at year end of ₱1,014 million for the reciprocal accounts. These GL and SL balances should have equal amount since details in the SL should support the GL balance; and 

effect any adjustment if any once the reconciliation has been done to be able to eliminate the difference in the reciprocal accounts.

We recommended that Management:

direct the concerned municipal officials to observe rules and regulations on budgeting, especially those mandated by DBM Local Budget Circulars, to ensure valid and legal appropriations and realignment of scarce available funds;

require the Municipal Accountant to revert the unexpended LDRRMF accrued in the trust fund beyond five years to be used in other social services programs of the Municipality;

require the concerned offices to immediately submit the lacking documentary requirements and disbursement vouchers to impede issuance of a Notice of Suspension/disallowance; and

refrain from charging disbursements against the LDRRMF which are not disaster-related and are disallowable under the governing provisions on its utilization.

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

record an adjusting entry in the books of the subsequent fiscal year to recognize Due to Officers and Employees account and derecognize Accounts Payable for any benefits included in the ₱2.184 million which remained unpaid as of this writing; and

refrain from recording Accounts Payable for transactions that do not fall under its prescribed description to avoid overstatement of such account and understatement of another liability account where the transaction should have been recorded;

We recommended that the Management through the MSWDO and Officer in charge of the SAP:

initiate efforts to address the noted variances, to wit: (1) the actual number of beneficiaries versus those encoded in the system, to account for the amount of ₱775,000.00; 

the profile of the 227 recipients who received the P1.14 million of the SAP but were not included in the SACUP, to determine their eligibility; 

the issue on 31 recipients corresponding to P155,000.00, to ensure that no duplication of recipients on the benefits granted.

We recommended that Management:

send demand letters to the concerned AOs to enforce the liquidation of their cash advances;

require the Accountable Officers concerned to settle/liquidate immediately their outstanding cash advances and the concerned officials to adhere strictly to the rules and regulations in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances provided under COA Circular 97-002;

enforce the appropriate sanctions provided by rules and regulations upon failure by the concerned AOs despite their receipt of the demand letter issued by the Municipal Accountant; and  

ensure that outstanding cash advances are liquidated prior to separation from office by any appointed or elected officer or employee.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor initiate the following measures to ensure correctness of the Road Networks account: 

create an Inventory Committee, preferably composed of one personnel each from the municipal Planning and Development Office; Engineering Office; Treasurer’s Office; General Services Office; Accountant’s Office and Assessor Office who shall conduct, on a full-time basis and within specified time, inspection and inventory of all road networks;

require the created inventory committee to conduct a physical count/inventory of all the municipal roads and reconcile it with the Municipal Road Map, if any and determine the existence and condition of the road components of each road for proper measurement and valuation using the prescribed forms such as: a) Local Road and Bridge Inventory and Condition Survey; b) Report of Local Road Network; and c) Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network;

direct the Municipal Accounting Office to: gather all details and information needed to determine the cost of the road lot, road components and  depreciable life of each road network and reconcile it with the recorded cost in the Registry of Public Infrastructure and existing ledgers;  prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the recognition of Public Infrastructure - Roads, Highways and Bridges in the General Ledger amounting to ₱30,117,502.22 as of December 31, 2019 ensuring that the accounting and reporting procedures laid down under COA Circular 2015-008  are fully complied by the concerned offices while the same procedure shall be undertaken for other public infrastructures accounts; 

instruct the Municipal Accounting Office and the General Services Office to strictly prepare and maintain all the prescribed reports under COA Circular 2015-008; 

require the Municipal Planning and Development Office to maintain the information on the local road network of the MGB, particularly, the plans and programs of the construction, repair and maintenance of local roads and the depreciable life of the road networks in coordination with the Engineering Office;

direct the Municipal Engineering Office to ensure that the Local Road Network map is aligned to the requirement of a road map described under the DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2017-159 and Local Roads Assets Management Manual for LGUs;  and, as the Office that undertakes the construction and repair of the local roads, documents relative thereto shall be maintained so that the necessary and detailed information of a certain road project, such as complete description of the road and the cost segregation of the road components are available anytime needed by the accounting and general services office and other stakeholders;

require the Municipal Assessor’s Office to prepare and maintain the tax maps, which is used as basis for identifying the ownership of all the road lots in the of  city road network and shall  also assist in determining the cost of the road lots with no available costs; and 

instruct the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to gather and keep in her vault documents regarding the ownership or acquisition of road land or road right of way through purchase, donation or any other modes of acquisition.

We recommended that Management:

direct the Municipal Budget Officer to include the estimated receipts from Special Education Tax and Rent Income in the breakdown of Estimated Revenues to fairly report the total targeted collections for the year;

exert stringent efforts in the collection of local taxes from its constituents;

tap all possible sources of income in order to substantially augment the revenues that can be used for the financial operation of the Municipality; and

remind taxpayers of their reciprocal obligations to pay their taxes on time which are ultimately given back by the government in the form of benefits/services.

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accounting Office to:

	gather the details/information records, and other alternative documents needed to determine the components of local roads identified in the inventory;

	segregate and recognize the cost of each component of the local roads with identified cost and recognize component without corresponding cost at its fair value;

	depreciate the carrying amount of existing roads and its components to reflect the asset in its used condition and shall serve as the basis for recording in the general ledger; 
	determine the life of the local roads within the range prescribed by COA taking into consideration the following factors:  a. design b. users c. volume of users; 

	compute separately the depreciation for the road components taking into consideration the initial cost and useful life.

	ensure that the details and information must be indicated in the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card - Local Road Network Ledger Card prepared and maintained for each item of road network;

	re-compute the accumulated depreciation and depreciation expense from CY 2016 to CY 2019 and thereafter adjust the affected accounts and the net book value of each of the asset; and 

	prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the year-end balances of the Public Infrastructure and Government Equity accounts.

